Title: Failure Analysis and Mishap Prevention Technologies                                                                                    17.828      17.972         18.044
Description: This operationally responsive effort rapidly identifies, generates and deploys solutions for time-critical material
and process challenges impacting weapon system capability across the life cycle — from research and development through
acquisition and operations. This accelerated approach focuses on delivering timely knowledge and technical insight to accelerate
advanced system development, reduce production and fielding risk, increase operational capability and prevent system mishaps.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue to rapidly respond to electronic and structure failure investigations and to transition materials and processing lessons
learned to promote mishap prevention and accelerated system solutions.
- Continue the research and development of improved materials and processing analysis techniques, nondestructive inspection
and test methods to prevent material system failure/degradation in production and in service.
- Continue the development and prototyping of advanced materials and processing solutions, including technology implementation
support, to accelerate warfighter system availability and enhance flight safety.
- Continue the refinement of the development and application of material system failure analysis capabilities to include metals,
polymer matrix composites, elastomers, adhesives, electronics, electrical systems and others.
- Continue the analysis and validation of advanced high power and electrostatic discharge protection technologies and procedures
for emerging systems, avionics subsystems and support processes.
- Continue the transition of advanced material processing, characterization, and procedural methods into the Department of War/
national specifications and standards to ensure the stability, quality, and safety of emerging electrical and structural materials and
processes.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Continue to rapidly respond to electrical and structural failure investigations and to transition material and process lessons
learned to promote mishap prevention, design/production risk reduction and accelerated system solutions.

                                                                                                                              Sustainment

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                  FY 2025      FY 2026         FY 2027
- Continue the research and development of improved material and process analysis techniques, nondestructive inspection (NDI)
and material/mechanical test methods to prevent material system failure/degradation in demonstration, testing, production and in
service
- Continue the development and prototyping of advanced material and processing solutions, including technology implementation
support, that accelerates warfighter system development, production, fielding and availability with enhanced flight safety.
- Continue the refinement of the development and application of material system failure analysis, aerospace mishap investigation
and other lab evaluation capabilities to include application of metals, polymer matrix composites, elastomers, adhesives,
electronics, electrical systems, chemical analysis, mechanical test, NDI, counterfeit and other necessary material and process
competencies.
- Continue the analysis and validation of advanced high power and electrostatic discharge test, characterization and protection
methods for operations, emerging systems, avionics subsystems and support processes.
- Continue the transition of advanced material processing, characterization, inspection, quality control and repair methods into
the Department of War policy for military/national specifications and standards to enable accelerated cost competitive and safe
implementation of material and process technology on current and future weapon systems.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
Funding in FY 2027 increased by $0.072 million compared to FY 2026 due to programmatic adjustments to the DAF Science and
Technology portfolio toward higher strategic priorities.
