INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604317F$$, 2027, $$Technology Transfer is a critical part of the National Defense Strategy (NDS) and Department of War (DoW) that makes the best possible use of national scientific,
technical resources and information to enhance the effectiveness of DoW forces and warfighting capability systems.

 The Department of the Air Force (DAF) Technology Transfer and Transition (T3) program oversees all of the DAF inventions/patents and technology transfer
 agreements, such as Cooperative Research and Development agreements (CRADAs), Material Transfer Agreements (MTAs), Confidential Disclosure Agreements
 (CDAs), etc. Over its history, Tech Transfer has provided a great return on investment (over 100 to one), as the agreements themselves do not provide DoW funding to
 companies/non-traditionals, but serve as a way for the DoW to partner together and with industry to achieve a common goal.

 The DAF Tech Transfer & Transition Program Office manages two DoW-level Partnership Intermediaries (PIAs), TechLink & MilTech (Montana State University) and
 assists the Office of the Deputy Assistant Secretary for Technology, Engineering & Product Support (SAF/AQT) in the management and oversight of the 14 DAF PIAs.
 This program element resources the management of DoW/DAF PIAs; the development of data to support the Defense Technology Transfer Information System (DTTIS);
 invention disclosure & patent processing; program management activities; and support to the Air Force Research Laboratory's (AFRL) Technology Executive Officer
 (TEO). This program impacts virtually all technology fields, including the DoW Critical Technology Areas, and facilitates mechanisms to help achieve the operational
 imperatives via Tech Transfer as captured in the Annual DoW Technology Transfer Report.

 In order to manage, execute, and deliver technology transfer capabilities, this program element may include: necessary civilian pay expenses; expenses to support the
 operation and maintenance of facilities; as well as expenses related to travel, supplies, IT hardware, software and support, etc.

 This effort is in Budget Activity 4, Advanced Component Development and Prototypes (ACD&P), because efforts are necessary to evaluate integrated technologies,
 representative modes or prototype systems in a high fidelity and realistic operating environment.
Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)$$, $$The Department of the Air Force (DAF) Tech Transfer & Transition Program Office Tech Transfer & Transition Program Office manages two Department of War (DoW)
level Partnership Intermediaries (PIAs) (TechLink & MilTech), supports oversight of 15 DAF PIAs, and oversees all DAF inventions/patents and technology transfer
agreements.

 Enabled by the TechLink PIA, TechLink brokered 80% of DoW license agreements over the past five years, with 90% of them being with small businesses. TechLink has
 also facilitated over 2,000 DoW tech transfer agreements since 1999 and has enabled the conversion of lab inventions into realized products and services that bolster
 the US Defense Innovation Ecosystem.

 Montana State University's MilTech has performed over 600 technology acceleration and transition projects for all DoW Services, OSW, Joint and Special Programs.
 Additionally, MilTech has partnered will all DoW Services for over twenty years to support efforts such as electronic warfare, medical technologies and body armor
 projects and has been selected as the permanent bi-annual host of the Interservice Body Armor Working Group (IBAWG) event. Montana State University's MilTech has
 been rated as a Top Ten Veteran Friendly university and has supported MilTech's 20 years of successful technology transitions that protect Soldiers, Sailors, Airmen,
 Marines, and Guardians.

 This project funds the management of DoW/DAF PIAs, invention disclosure & patent processing, program management activities, training, support to the Technology
 Executive Officer (TEO), and support of the Defense Technology Transfer Information System (DTTIS). This DTTIS platform collects and manages technology transfer
 activities.

