This program, BA 5, PE 0604270F, project , Talon LURCHER, is a new start.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Cognitive Electromagnetic Warfare (Cog EW) integrates multiple projects to achieve massed non-kinetic warfare dominance for the DoW Counter Long-Range Kill Chain
(C-LRKC) and Counter-Command, Control, Communications, Computers, Cyber, Intelligence, Surveillance, & Reconnaissance (C-C5ISR) constructs. This funding
increase adds two new interrelated activities and more expenditures on a current project in order to capture, employ, and exploit EW effectiveness improvements/
synergies in contested/congested battlespaces.

 The Modular Electromagnetic Attack Payloads (MEAP) project will, as part of the overall Cognitive EW Capabilities program, demonstrate and deliver advanced (e.g.,
 using AI, ML, and Cognitive technologies) modularized (defined by size, weight, power/cooling, function, and interface standards) techniques for one (or more) threshold
 platform s. The intent is to provide an Electromagnetic Attack capability that can be adapted to a number of appropriate platforms to yield a massed non-kinetic fires
 effect.

 The Exploitation Application project is the transition of two Air Force Tactical Exploitation of National Capabilities (TENCAP) programs to the operational Air Force.
 TENCAP increases warfighter effectiveness and promotes cross-domain integration by pursuing multiple small projects then transitioning them via rapid prototyping and
 capability demonstrations. This project consists of an aiming system to enable a separate firing system designed to effect satellite operations.

 The Talon LURCHER system will fil key requirement for engaging targets at hypersonic speeds and extended ranges while synchronizing the entire effects chain.
 The management of these effects must be based on a multi-variable solution that accounts for time, space, range, and velocity relative to the target's specifications.
 Delivering non-atmospheric effects against targets moving at speeds greater than Mach 20 introduces significant challenges related to data latency. Therefore, this effort
 will develop and integrate technology specifically designed to alleviate these delays in the track and fire control loop while enabling consistent and accurate delivery of
 effects to fast-moving, long-range targets, serving as the key technical enabler to properly AIM the weapon system.

 The Talon UPCYLE system will utilize existing COMPASS CALL SPEAR Gen 3 pods with current hardware and software to develop tactical counter-space EW systems.
 The systems will FIRE counter P-LEO techniques to degrade, deny, disrupt, and deceive SIGINT and IFTU satellites.



